<HL>
   Letters to the Editor:
   Kristol Is Wrong About Lithuania
</HL>
<DATE>
05/15/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A25
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST
</CO>
<LP>
   Though I am not of Lithuanian ancestry, I am revolted by
Irving Kristol's April 11 editorial-page article, "Bush Is
Right About Lithuania," purporting to demonstrate the
hopelessness of Lithuania's independence drive. The article,
and the fact that it appeared in The Wall Street Journal of
all places, no doubt is as cheering to the Kremlin as it is
depressing for the embattled Lithuanians.
   Mr. Kristol states he is confused by Mikhail Gorbachev's
policies and actions with regard to Lithuania. I don't find
them confusing. They change by the moment because Mr.
Gorbachev is a consummate opportunist and politician who
subscribes to communist ideology. Thus, he will do whatever
it takes to achieve the desired results (maintaining Soviet
power as well as his own) while not disturbing the balance of
power within the various factions of his own government or in
the West.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Most offensive is Mr. Kristol's assertion that "Lithuania
is not a lucky country" and the conclusion that independence
is impossible for "the foreseeable future," as if "luck" had
anything to do with the principles that should guide American
actions toward a small nation that so closely shares our
ideals.
   The desperate state of the Soviet economy and growing
unrest in other parts of the Soviet empire imply that no one,
certainly not Mr. Kristol, knows what will happen there.
There are a number of scenarios under which Lithuanian
independence is not only possible, but probable. One of them
is the scenario under which Lithuania receives strong moral
and diplomatic support from the West.
   Ann Donnelly
   Vancouver, Wash.
   ---
   I was stung by Mr. Kristol's article. As a recent
Lithuanian-American traveler and business consultant in the
U.S.S.R., I am highly motivated to respond:
   First, his comparison of Vietnam to Lithuania is
ludicrous. In Vietnam there was a civil war between opposing
factions. Lithuania had enjoyed centuries of independence
prior to the Soviet takeover of its sovereignty.
   Second, Mr. Gorbachev did not "incite the Lithuanians to
declare their independence from the U.S.S.R." -- they have
sought independence for decades, including seven years of
freedom fighting from 1945 to 1952.
   Third, the Soviet Constitution, Article 17, states the
right of any republic to withdraw from the U.S.S.R. through
democratic means, which is exactly what Lithuania did.
   Last, but most important, Lithuania is, in fact, a lucky
country -- a very lucky country -- with a rich history; a
colorful, peaceful culture; one of the oldest, most beautiful
languages in the world; and 3.7 million peace-loving, proud,
industrious people who have survived much stress and
persecution.
   Michael D. Pavilon
   Chicago
   ---
   In regard to Mr. Kristol's article:
   1. Although "no nation has ever recognized a right of
secession," since when has the U.S. or any other
freedom-loving country recognized a "right of forced
belonging"? Remember -- the Baltics were invaded and forcibly
absorbed into the Soviet Union.
   2. Lithuania, Latvia and Estonia are not part of the
"centuries-old Russian empire." Only for the past 50 years
have they been forced to be part of the U.S.S.R.
   3. Lithuania is not a "lucky" country because insensitive,
uncaring and so-called rationalizing intelligentsia such as
Mr. Kristol will not give it support.
   Anthony J. Lisauskas
   Naperville, Ill.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900515-0135
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900515-0135.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Who's News:
   Sylvia Picked to Run
   Nuclear Operations
   At Niagara Mohawk
</HL>
<DATE>
05/15/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A11
</SO>
<CO>
   NMK WNEWS
</CO>
<LP>
   DETROIT -- B. Ralph Sylvia, Detroit Edison Co.'s top
nuclear executive, resigned to run Niagara Mohawk Power Co.'s
troubled nuclear power operations.
   In his four years with Detroit Edison, Mr. Sylvia became
known as a top nuclear trouble-shooter for turning around the
Fermi 2 nuclear plant near Detroit, which had huge cost
overruns, years of delays and frequent regulatory run-ins.
Most recently he was senior vice president, nuclear
generation, at Detroit Edison.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   At Niagara Mohawk, the 49-year-old Mr. Sylvia will again
face a difficult situation. The Syracuse, N.Y., utility is
trying to gain Nuclear Regulatory Commission approval to
restart its Nine Mile Point No. 1 plant, which was shut down
in 1987. Company officials said they met with NRC
commissioners yesterday to set a date for the resumption of
power production at the plant. They said they expect to have
it working again by the end of next month. Meanwhile, Niagara
Mohawk's No. 2 nuclear plant has progressed slowly since its
start-up in mid-1987.
   When he starts at Niagara Mohawk on July 1, Mr. Sylvia
will temporarily serve as senior vice president of nuclear
operations. Later this year, he will become executive vice
president of nuclear operations, succeeding Lawrence
Burkhardt III, a Niagara Mohawk board member and retired Navy
admiral who took the executive vice president's job 1 1/2
years ago on a contract basis.
   Detroit Edison said William S. Orser will succeed Mr.
Sylvia. Mr. Orser, 45, has been vice president, nuclear
operations, since 1987 and was closely involved with the
Fermi 2 plant improvements.
   Mr. Sylvia's departure is the second change involving top
Detroit Edison executives this month. On May 1, John E.
Lobbia was named Detroit Edison's chairman and chief
executive officer in addition to his previous posts of
president and chief operating officer.
   The top-level changes and the loss of a key executive
sparked concern from analysts. "You have to watch very
carefully when a company that has experienced problems loses
some of the management that helped improve the situation,"
said James K. Asselstine, an electric utility credit analyst
with Shearson Lehman Hutton. "We'll especially watch Detroit
Edison because while Fermi 2 has improved substantially, it
continues to perform below average."
   In New York Stock Exchange composite trading yesterday,
Detroit Edison stock closed at $26.75 a share, down 50 cents.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900515-0134
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900515-0134.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Platinum Output
   By South Africa
   Is Expected to Grow
   ----
   By Neil Behrmann
   Special to The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/15/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C15
</SO>
<CO>
   AFRIC
</CO>
<IN>
PRECIOUS METALS, STONES, GOLD, SILVER (PCS)
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
</IN>
<LP>
   LONDON -- South African platinum mines are planning to
raise production by one million troy ounces, or 39%, during
the next five years, Johnson Matthey PLC said in its latest
annual review of the metal.
   This year, the world's largest platinum producing nation
will produce as much as 150,000 ounces more than 1989's
record output of nearly 2.6 million ounces, the
precious-metals-refinery firm said.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   However, in futures trading, platinum prices rose to
$485.75 an ounce, up $2, on expectations that strikes and
strife in South Africa will pare the mines' estimates during
the next few years.
   Moreover, dealers responded favorably to Johnson Matthey's
findings that exports by the Soviet Union, the second-largest
producer, were sharply lower in this year's first quarter.
   Last year, Soviet platinum supplies soared to 550,000
ounces, the highest levels since 1977, Johnson Matthey said.
Yet production fell this year, possibly because of an
explosion in November at a platinum-producing complex in
Norilsk, Siberia, said Jeremy Coombes, author of the report.
   Although the Soviet Union could well raise sales later in
the year, he said, total exports this year could decline to
1988 levels of 440,000 ounces.
   Meanwhile, world-wide fabrication demand rose to
approximately 3.2 million ounces in 1989 from approximately
three million in 1988, mainly because of buoyant jewelry
demand in Japan. Platinum used in automobiles also grew.
   But investment in platinum bars and coins tumbled 75% to
160,000 ounces last year, from 660,000 ounces in 1988,
because of high real returns on other investments, Mr.
Coombes said.
   Growth in industrial demand could also slacken, Johnson
Matthey said. Faced with higher borrowing costs, industrial
consumers may prefer to reduce inventories rather than buy
new metal. Platinum sales could also be hindered by weaker
U.S. auto production, and after five successive years of
growth, platinum consumption in Western Europe may also
stagnate.
   Excluding investment demand, supplies exceeded fabrication
consumption by 110,000 ounces, the third year of surplus, the
report said. But with such a narrow differential between
demand and supply, prices could range between $470 and $520
an ounce this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
