<HL>
   Enterprise:
   Senate Looking Into Some Health-Insurance Pooling
   ---
   `Unscrupulous Promoters' of MEWAs
   Cause Problems for Small Businesses
   ----
   By John R. Emshwiller
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/15/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B2
</SO>
<CO>
   LABOR
</CO>
<IN>
INSURANCE (INS)
</IN>
<GV>
LABOR DEPARTMENT (LBR)
CONGRESS (CNG)
</GV>
<LP>
   For small businesses, MEWA is becoming a four-letter word.
   A few years ago, having small businesses band together
into Multiple Employer Welfare Associations struck many
business owners as a great way to get cheaper health care.
But today, the Senate Permanent Subcommittee on
Investigations is scheduled to hold a hearing in Washington
on MEWA fraud and abuse. "Unscrupulous promoters . . . are
literally playing with people's lives," says subcommittee
chairman Sam Nunn (D., Ga.).
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Says Raymond Maria, the Labor Department's acting
inspector general: "The whole environment is an invitation to
larceny." Law-enforcement officials say MEWAs have fallen in
the cracks between state and federal oversight.
   Those and other problems with MEWAs have left many
business owners disillusioned. For instance, Jo Hardwick, the
owner of a real-estate agency in Cape Coral, Fla., signed
herself and some of her employees into a MEWA when she found
it difficult to get traditional health insurance. "We paid
our premiums, and then the problems started," she recalls.
Ms. Hardwick says she is out $1,100 in premiums and has had
to pay $8,000 of medical bills that were supposed to be
covered.
   According to testimony prepared by the Texas Board of
Insurance for today's Senate hearing, principals of Ms.
Hardwick's MEWA, which also operated in Texas, used premium
dollars to lease luxury cars, do construction work on their
homes and buy expensive suits and jewelry.
   James Helm, a principal of the MEWA, last month in a
deposition in a Texas state court denied wasting premium
dollars.
   To be sure, law-enforcement officials and others familiar
with MEWAs note that many MEWAs are operating successfully
and some MEWA failures are due to factors other than
chicanery. Robert van Maarth, the Lakewood, Colo.,
administrator of several MEWAs, says such plans are "still a
marvelous idea" when they are properly run and regulated.
   MEWAs, which are supposed to act as self-insurance pools
or as purchasers of group policies from insurance companies,
have proliferated as small companies cope with soaring health
costs and difficulty in getting standard coverage.
   Nobody seems to know the precise dimensions of MEWA fraud,
or even the total number of MEWAs. But state and federal
officials who have begun investigating corruption in these
benefit plans estimate that unpaid medical claims probably
reach into the hundreds of millions of dollars and affect
hundreds of thousands of workers.
   For the small-business owner, the financial danger from
failed MEWAs can be enormous. Patricia Petersen, a deputy
insurance commissioner for the state of Washington, says
employers could be held liable under federal law for any
unpaid medical bills of their employees.
   In the case of Zapata Bancshares Inc., unpaid claims total
several hundred thousand dollars, says Laura Miller, who
handles claims for the bank holding company, based in Zapata,
Texas. (In 1989, Zapata's net income was $365,000.) The
company hopes to recover at least some of the money from the
operators and insurance brokers involved with the same
multistate MEWA used by Ms. Hardwick's firm.
   A federal creation in the mid-1970s under the purview of
the Labor Department, MEWAs were largely unregulated by
either the state or federal government. By the early 1980s,
enough MEWA problems were surfacing that Congress gave states
their own powers to oversee the plans (then generally known
as Multiple Employer Trusts, or METs). But most states still
looked to the federal government for the lead in regulating
MEWAs.
   In Washington state, Ms. Petersen says her office has
received increasing numbers of complaints about MEWAs. Among
other things, insurance regulators found that the person
running one MEWA previously had his securities licenses in
two states revoked for absconding with clients' funds, Ms.
Petersen says.
   Ms. Petersen called on the Labor Department for help,
partly because MEWA administrators were turning away state
investigators, claiming federal jurisdiction. "We just needed
a federal body to get through the doors," she says. "But the
Labor Department wouldn't do it."
   Tom Gallagher, Florida's insurance commissioner, says the
state has spent a lot of time fighting in court over MEWAs'
claims of federal exemption from state regulation. MEWAs
"keep taking people's money and not paying claims," he says.
   Labor Department infighting may be hampering moves against
MEWA abuse. Mr. Maria, the acting inspector general, who has
about two dozen criminal MEWA investigations under way, says
he could triple such activity if not for restrictions on his
role. (Bills have recently been introduced in Congress to
give inspectors general broader investigative power.)
   But David George Ball, an assistant secretary of labor,
says the pension and welfare office has responsibility over
MEWAs and has some 40 civil and criminal probes of its own
under way.
   Mr. Ball declines to comment on the department's past
handling of the MEWA issue but says that in recent months it
has "brought tremendous amounts of new resources to bear" on
MEWA problems. He says Labor Secretary Elizabeth Dole just
yesterday sent a letter to each state insurance commissioner
presenting a program for cooperating in investigating MEWAs.
   Meanwhile, entrepreneurs can take some steps to protect
themselves, say lawenforcement officials. Their advice:
   -- Research any MEWA thoroughly. Get the names of people
running it and find out what jobs they've had before. Check
with regulators in states where they worked to see if there
were any problems.
   -- Ask for a financial plan for the MEWA and get it
evaluated by an independent expert. "Our experience is that
the worst frauds generally won't show you a financial
statement," says James Harrington, a supervising investigator
with the California state insurance department.
   -- Press insurance agents on exactly what they are
selling. Some employers complain that insurance agents tell
them they are getting coverage through an insurance company
when in truth they are being sold a MEWA.
   -- Once in a plan, keep an eye on it. The federal MEWA
legislation envisions employers' being active members of the
MEWA boards of trustees, says Washington's Ms. Petersen. But
all too often, she adds, employers "just leave the fox
sitting there alone."
   ---
   Eugene Carlson contributed to this article.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900515-0083
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900515-0083.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Who's News:
   Sallie Mae Chief Executive
   Named Dean at Dartmouth
</HL>
<DATE>
05/15/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10
</SO>
<CO>
   SLM WNEWS
</CO>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- Edward A. Fox, president and chief executive
officer of the Student Loan Marketing Association, was named
dean of Dartmouth University's Amos Tuck School of business.
   Mr. Fox, 53 years old, succeeds Colin C. Blaydon, 49, who
will return to teaching after taking a sabbatical to work on
a book.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   As Sallie Mae's first and only chief executive officer,
Mr. Fox oversaw the student-loan servicing concern's
evolution from a company with "a net worth of negative
$50,000 on my first day" 17 years ago to one with assets of
$37 billion.
   Mr. Fox has taught at Georgetown University and the
business schools of New York University, the University of
Pennsylvania, and Harvard University.
   The new dean said he intends to recruit more women and
minority students and faculty to meet the changing
demographic nature of the work force. "Women and minorities
are replacing retiring white males," Mr. Fox said. "We should
have more managers that come from those environments."
   Sallie Mae said its board will meet next week to begin its
search for a successor to Mr. Fox, who will step down in late
summer. Separately, the company said Ronald F. Hunt,
executive vice president and general counsel, resigned,
effective July. Mr. Hunt, 46, will pursue private practice in
his native North Carolina.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900515-0082
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900515-0082.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Abreast of the Market:
   Industrial Stocks Rally to Record
   Of 2821.53 as Volume Stays High
   ----
   By David Wilson
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/15/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C2
</SO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
STOCK INDEXES (NDX)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- The stock market rallied to a record high on
the Dow Jones Industrial Average as encouraging prospects for
interest rates and inflation continued to push investors off
the sidelines.
   Prices closed well below the day's best levels, however,
as profit-taking surfaced in the afternoon amid speculation
that the market had overdone its advance.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "There's a lot of people that are still saying, `We've got
to correct. We've gone too far too fast,'" said Dale Tills,
manager of institutional equities trading at Charles Schwab &amp;
Co., San Francisco.
   The industrial average gave back most of its gains but
managed to finish 19.95 higher at 2821.53 -- above the
previous record of 2810.15, established Jan. 2.
   After surging 63.07 points Friday, the Dow industrial
average tacked on an additional 52 points through midday as a
result of continued buying interest from institutional
investors seeking to offset short positions, and some
occasional bursts of futures-related program buying.
   In the process, the average surpassed its best-ever
intraday reading with ease. On Jan. 3, the 30-stock measure
had peaked at 2834.04; in the latest session, it exceeded
that mark by nearly 20 points.
   Broader market indexes, hampered by their relatively weak
performance in comparison to the Dow industrial average over
the past few months, didn't come close to setting record
highs of their own.
   Standard &amp; Poor's 500-Stock Index closed 1.4% below its
all-time high of 359.80, set last Oct. 9. Also, the New York
Stock Exchange Composite Index and the Dow Jones Equity
Market Index finished 2.9% and 2.4%, respectively, below the
all-time high set on the same day.
   In the latest session, the S&amp;P 500 gained 2.75 to 354.75,
while the composite index added 1.41 to 193.65, and the Dow
equity index went up 2.68 to 329.74. Advancing issues led
decliners by 1,062 to 555 on the Big Board.
   Market activity remained brisk with 225,410,000 shares
changing hands. The volume was the second highest this year
on the Big Board, outranked only by Friday's total of
234,040,000.
   Among technical analysts, who focus on market statistics
in assessing the outlook for stock prices, the broad market's
relatively weak performance in comparison to the Dow
industrial average has been a source of concern for some
time.
   But some technicians said the situation appears likely to
change for the better in the wake of Friday's surge, in which
the number of shares traded above their previous close on the
Big Board topped the volume of decliners by a margin of more
than 19-to-1.
   The ratio of advancing volume to declining volume has
exceeded 9-to-1 only two dozen times in the past 30 years,
according to a study by Richard Eakle, president of Eakle
Associates, a Fair Haven, N.J.-based research firm.
   The study found that stock prices were higher three months
later in 19 of those 24 instances. Six months later, the
market was higher all but once -- in the aftermath of the
October 1987 crash -- and the Dow industrial average showed
an average gain of 17.3%.
   In addition, Mr. Eakle says, measures of the market's
breadth, or the relationship between advancing and declining
stocks, appear to be "inextricably linked to trends in
interest rates." With rates having fallen recently, further
strength in the broad market can be anticipated, he says.
   Ned Davis, a technical analyst based in Venice, Fla., says
the market could be headed for "an upside blow-off," citing
the new high in the Dow industrial average, high levels of
cash and short interest among investors, and indications that
many market players remain pessimistic in spite of the
market's strength.
   If such a blow-off takes place, Mr. Davis says, two
possible targets would emerge for the industrial average --
"just below 3000 if people turn bullish rapidly and everyone
is focused on 3000 as a target," or 3180, representing 30
times his estimate of $106 in 1990 dividend payments for the
30 stocks in the average.
   Du Pont rallied 1 3/4 to 40 3/8 in Big Board composite
trading of 2.6 million shares. Mabon Nugent upgraded its
investment rating on the stock to "buy" from "neutral" and
raised its earnings estimates for 1990 and 1991.
   Federal National Mortgage Association, the most active Big
Board issue, dropped 7/8 to 37 7/8 on 4.1 million shares as
selected financial stocks became a target for profit-taking
after setting the pace for Friday's surge. The stock reached
40 5/8 before pulling back in the afternoon.
   Progressive climbed 1 7/8 to 40. The Wall Street Journal
reported in the "Heard on the Street" column that analysts
believe the company will benefit from other insurers'
pullbacks from the auto insurance market.
   International Business Machines rose 1/4 to 114 1/4 on 2.3
million shares, but other major technology issues fared
better with investors. Digital Equipment went up 1 7/8 to 90
1/2, Compaq Computer gained 2 to 112 3/8, and Hewlett-Packard
rose 1 1/4 to 48 3/8 on 1.7 million shares.
   Prime Motor Inns advanced 1 3/4 to 12 1/8 on 1.7 million
shares in the wake of Manor Care's expression of interest in
making a bid for the company's Howard Johnson and Ramada
franchise systems. As previously reported, Prime Motor agreed
in principle to sell a 65% stake in the systems to Blackstone
Capital Partners for about $200 million in cash and notes.
   USX rose 1 to 34 1/4 on 1.9 million shares following a
favorable review of the company in Barron's magazine from
Frederick Leuffer, an analyst at C.J. Lawrence, Morgan
Grenfell. He said the stock's intrinsic value, based on a
variety of measures, is around $50 a share.
   Atlantic Richfield jumped 2 7/8 to 118 3/4. In a 7-2
ruling, the Supreme Court threw out an antitrust lawsuit
against the company by independent gas stations in California
and Washington state.
   W.R. Grace advanced 3/4 to 28 1/2 after news that
California officials are testing a new kind of catalytic
converter, manufactured by the company's Camet unit.
   Mylan Laboratories went down 1 1/4 to 22 5/8. The company
acknowledged to Dow Jones Professional Investor Report that
April sales of Eldepryl, a drug produced by a joint venture
of Mylan and Bolar Pharmaceutical, fell more than 7% from the
March level. Bolar dropped 5/8 to 7 1/2 in American Stock
Exchange trading.
   The Amex Market Value Index rose 1.84 to 354.34, its 11th
straight advance, but remained well below the all-time high
of 397.03 set last Oct. 10. Volume totaled 16,170,000 shares
compared with 16,600,000 Friday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
