<HL>
   REVIEW &amp; OUTLOOK (Editorial):
   `Hatch 22'
</HL>
<DATE>
05/15/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A24
</SO>
<CO>
   LABOR
</CO>
<LP>
   "Catch 22" is a famous metaphor for a bad deal -- for
example, you can't get a job without experience, but you
can't get experience without a job. Congress is now trying to
create what a few wags are calling a "Hatch 22" -- federal
employees will be allowed to wage partisan politics but still
be protected by civil-service laws.
   In other words, a typical Washington deal, good for
everyone except taxpayers.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   That about sums up the current effort to amend the Hatch
Act, the 1939 law that bars the three-million-strong federal
work force from partisan politics. The Senate voted 67-30
last week to all but repeal the act's political curbs, and
the House passed a similar bill last year. President Bush has
promised a veto, but an override vote will be close.
   No one wants to deny federal workers the basic rights of
citizenship. They can vote as they like. But repealing the
Hatch Act would allow employees to become full-fledged
partisans -- raising money, running for office,
electioneering, organizing political-action committees.
Indeed, this is precisely the plan of the public-employee
unions that are driving the bill. Their leaders are
frustrated that the Hatch Act limits their political clout.
The presidents of three unions were suspended for 60 days
under Hatch for openly supporting Walter Mondale in 1984.
   If the Hatch curbs are dumped, these unions will become
giant lobbies for their own self-interest, which is to say
for a bigger state. Somehow the idea persists in Washington
that serious policy should be turned over to "disinterested"
career civil servants. For relying mainly on political
appointees, Attorney General Dick Thornburgh is getting heat
from all over, only last week for disagreeing with his deputy
who was representing the career staff's point of view.
   But political appointees are at least subject to politics
-- to presidential elections. An un-Hatched civil service
will get the best of both worlds, both the right to play
politics and protection from voters. Thus insulated, this
force will soon conspire with the other nearly permanent
branch of government, the Congress and its staff. Voting will
mean even less than it does now.
   Civil libertarians should also be worried, since Hatch
repeal would create big new opportunities for state coercion.
Do Americans really want the same people who audit taxes or
deliver the mail to hit them up for campaign gifts? It's
worth recalling that the Hatch Act was passed in response to
reports that New Deal foremen were strong-arming workers to
help re-elect a Kentucky Senator.
   The only way to protect civil servants from harassment is
to shield them from partisan politics altogether. Only a
total ban gives employees a plausible excuse for not becoming
political. Without such a ban, an employee will always feel
pressure, however subtle, to favor the boss's or union's
cause. Federal workers themselves seem to understand this;
polls have shown significant employee concern about Hatch
repeal.
   If the unions want to politicize the civil service, then
at least let's go all the way. Let's bring back the old
"spoils system" and make everything political. When everyone
was a political appointee, at least voters had the chance to
throw the bums out every four years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900515-0066
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900515-0066.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media -- Advertising:
   Waring &amp; LaRosa Scores Again,
   Picking Up Fisher-Price Work
   ----
   By Joanne Lipman
</HL>
<DATE>
05/15/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6
</SO>
<CO>
   OAT F.PRR OMCM WPPGY SAA
</CO>
<IN>
ADVERTISING, MARKETING, PUBLIC RELATIONS (ADV)
CORPORATE PROFILE (PRO)
RECREATION, ENTERTAINMENT, TOYS, MOVIES, PHOTOGRAPHY, SPORTS (REC)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   Waring &amp; LaRosa, a tiny New York ad agency that just last
year seemed near death's door, continued its startling
turnaround by picking up more than $20 million in
Fisher-Price toys business.
   Fisher-Price, a unit of Quaker Oats, said it would
consolidate all of its domestic consumer advertising with
Waring &amp; LaRosa, which already handles its $12 million infant
toys account. According to Leading National Advertisers,
Fisher-Price spent $36.7 million on advertising in 1989, but
industry executives said it is spending less this year,
reflecting lower toy sales.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The account had been split between Waring & LaRosa; Backer
Spielvogel Bates, which had the $15 million to $20 million
traditional toy account for toddlers; and J. Walter
Thompson's Chicago office, which created ads for promotional
products, an account billing just under $5 million.
   The Fisher-Price victory is the latest in a string of new
accounts for Waring &amp; LaRosa. In March, Perrier -- which
fired the ad agency in 1986 -- brought back its $8 million to
$10 million account to the shop to help with Perrier's
relaunch. Variations of an early 1980s Waring spot, featuring
a cartoon caveman discovering "the earth's first soft drink,"
are airing now. The Progresso sauce and Sunshine biscuit
accounts also signed on in the past six months.
   The agency also is a contender for the Heublein account,
including Finlandia vodka and Jose Cuervo tequila. And it was
a finalist in the hotly contested Reebok account, which
ultimately was awarded to Hill, Holliday, Connors,
Cosmopulos. Waring &amp; LaRosa, which by last fall had shrunk to
less than $50 million in billings, now bills well over $70
million, says Joseph LaRosa, chairman and creative director.
   The ad agency's winning streak is that much more
surprising considering how rocky its history has been over
the past few years. The agency, formed by partners Saul
Waring and Mr. LaRosa in 1968, quickly developed a hot
creative reputation, as did some others formed around the
same time, such as Scali, McCabe, Sloves. But Waring &amp;
LaRosa's fortunes took a turn for the worse in the early
1980s after it sold itself to BBDO, which subsequently became
part of the Omnicom Group.
   Soon after BBDO bought it, Waring's largest client,
Chesebrough-Pond's, pulled almost all of its account,
including the Aziza cosmetics, Cutex nail products, and
Prince tennis racket accounts. Fisher-Price, another major
client, pulled a big piece of its account next, with the
final blow coming when Perrier fired the agency.
   Meanwhile, attempts to win new business seemed blocked at
every turn, because almost every product category was already
handled by Omnicom's bigger ad units. Waring &amp; LaRosa had
lengthy discussions with Porsche, and received a letter of
interest from Jaguar, but couldn't take on a car account
because of bigger automotive accounts elsewhere within
Omnicom. "Every time we turned around we had a conflict," Mr.
LaRosa says.
   As a result, Waring, which billed $100 million when BBDO
bought it, billed just $50 million by early last year, when
it bought back its independence. Going it alone, though, at
first seemed just as miserable. Last November, Waring again
lost its largest account when Ragu, which at its height had
billed over $20 million, fired the agency.
   Since then, though, the agency has had a Phoenix-like
rise. Mr. LaRosa attributes the wave of new business to the
agency's emphasis on building brands, and to the fact that,
finally, it isn't saddled with conflicts.
   "Clients are starting to look for people like us. The
companies coming to us are packaged goods companies that want
good creative work," Mr. LaRosa says. "We think we've
overcome the odds."
   The Fisher-Price consolidation came as a shock to Backer
Spielvogel Bates. Backer attributed the move to a management
change in Fisher-Price's marketing department. David Fisher,
who had been executive vice president of North American
operations, resigned several weeks ago, and his advertising
duties were taken over by Strawn Cathcart, vice president of
marketing. Quaker recently announced plans to spin off
Fisher-Price.
   "The loss . . . came as a total surprise," a Backer
spokeswoman said. "The decision was certainly not a
reflection of the quality of our work . . . which has always
been superior, but a change in marketing management at
Fisher-Price." Backer continues to handle Fisher-Price's
advertising in Europe.
   Mr. Cathcart said the toy company decided to consolidate
at Waring &amp; LaRosa because the agency, which first took on
the account in 1969 when Fisher-Price was a small regional
company, helped build its national presence almost from
scratch. "We're going back to basics," Mr. Cathcart said,
"and we feel very comfortable putting our image into the
hands of the people who developed the business."
   ---
   Ad Notes. . . .
                                                                                                       

   FILM ADVERTISING: Spot television and the broadcast TV
networks posted the biggest dollar gains in the ad budgets of
U.S. film distributors in 1989, according to an analysis by
Blair Television. Spot TV spending last year jumped 15% to
$180 million, up from $156 million. Network ad spending by
the major film companies increased 14% to $207 million, up
from $181 million in 1988. Newspaper ad spending edged up to
$149 million from $147 million a year earlier.
                                                                                                       

   MERGER: DDB Needham, an Omnicom Group agency, said it
reached an agreement to merge Broucc DDB Needham, its office
in Milan, Italy, with Verba, another shop in Milan. The
agency, which will have billings of $100 million, will be
called Verba DDB Needham. Terms weren't disclosed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900515-0065
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900515-0065.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Pennsylvania Bill Would Bar Insurers
   Who Quit Auto Market From Other Lines
   ----
   By Beatrice E. Garcia
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/15/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4
</SO>
<CO>
   AET SAFC HGIC
</CO>
<IN>
INSURANCE (INS)
</IN>
<LP>
   HARRISBURG, Pa. -- Two state senators proposed legislation
that would bar insurers from selling new policies in all
other insurance lines if they decided to pull out of the auto
insurance business in Pennsylvania.
   There are also plans to amend an antitrust statute, being
considered by the state senate judiciary committee, removing
a current partial exemption for the insurance industry.
Pennsylvania is the only state without an antitrust law.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   However, Pennsylvania's fight to keep auto insurers from
bailing out of the state was dealt a blow when a state court
judge ruled last Friday that current Pennsylvania law doesn't
prevent an insurer from pulling out of the auto-insurance
market if staying costs the company more money than it would
make.
   The measure unveiled yesterday is designed to block three
insurers who sent nonrenewal notices to their auto insurance
policyholders in Pennsylvania. The proposed bill is similar
to a Massachusetts law that's being challenged in federal
court by Aetna Life &amp; Casualty Co., which claims it's
unconstitutional.
   A new auto insurance bill, signed into law in February,
requires premium rate rollbacks of 10% and as much as 22%, if
drivers choose a no-fault provision limiting their right to
sue. The measure proposed yesterday would be retroactive to
Jan. 1. The bill will be introduced in the senate later this
week.
   Auto insurers "who have pulled the rug out from under
Pennsylvania motorists should not be doing other new business
in the state," said State Senator Stewart J. Greenleaf, one
of the two sponsors of the new bill. If losing new business
in all their other insurance lines isn't enough of a
deterrent to keep auto insurers in Pennsylvania, then Sen.
Greenleaf said he would ask the legislature to bar companies
from all other business in this state.
   Aetna is one of the three insurers who want to pull out of
the auto insurance market. It said that the rate rollbacks
ordered by the new auto insurance law would force it to lose
about $20 million over the next 12 months. The Hartford,
Conn.-based company is the fifth-largest insurer working in
Pennsylvania, with 200,000 policyholders.
   Harleysville Mutual Insurance Co. and a unit of Safeco
Corp. have also sent nonrenewal notices to their
policyholders in Pennsylvania. They also claim the rollback
would hurt them.
   Officials at Harleysville and Safeco couldn't comment
until they'd reviewed a copy of the proposed legislation.
Aetna couldn't be reached.
   In ruling on a suit brought by Harleysville against the
state insurance commissioner, a Commonwealth Court said if an
insurer sustains "a signficant loss if they continue to issue
private passenger automobile insurance policies, that's "a
good reason" for nonrenewals.
   The state insurance department immediately appealed the
ruling to the state supreme court. Some state officials fear
a mass exodus by auto insurers if the lower court decision is
upheld.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
