<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900515-0059
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900515-0059.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   NASD Authorities
   Cancel Membership
   Of Wellshire Securities
</HL>
<DATE>
05/15/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C19
</SO>
<IN>
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
</IN>
<GV>
SECURITIES AND EXCHANGE COMMISSION (SEC)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The National Association of Securities
Dealers said it canceled the membership of Wellshire
Securities Inc., a penny-stock firm based in New York.
   The cancellation followed a preliminary injunction granted
by a federal court in Manhattan in April at the request of
the Securities and Exchange Commission. In March, the SEC
filed a civil suit alleging that Wellshire and its executives
made false and misleading statements about the stocks they
were promoting.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The SEC complaint said that from June 1988 to the present,
Wellshire, under the direction of Robert Cohen and Carol
Martino, has operated a penny-stock "boiler room," selling
speculative over-the-counter securities to the public through
the use of abusive sales practices and inflated price
predictions.
   "Wellshire and Cohen and Martino haven't been given the
benefit of a full trial," said Mitchell Lampert, an attorney
for the executives. "But the damage has already been done."
Wellshire and the two executives previously have denied any
wrongdoing.
</TEXT>
