<HL>
   Credit Rating:
   S&amp;P Lowers Ratings
   On Wells Fargo Debt
</HL>
<DATE>
05/15/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C23
</SO>
<CO>
   WFC
</CO>
<IN>
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
</IN>
<LP>
   SAN FRANCISCO -- Standard &amp; Poor's Corp. said it cut its
rating on Wells Fargo &amp; Co.'s senior debt to single-A-plus
from double-A-minus.
   The rating concern also downgraded the banking company's
commercial paper to single-A-minus from single-A-plus,
preferred stock to single-A-minus from single-A, and
letter-of-credit-backed issues to single-A-plus from
double-A-minus. In all, about $3.7 billion in debt is
affected.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   S&amp;P said the cuts reflect its concerns about the potential
effects of Wells Fargo's high exposure to commercial real
estate, as well as a major commitment to lending for highly
leveraged transactions.
   In a statement, Carl E. Reichardt, Wells Fargo's chairman,
described the S&amp;P action as "inappropriate."
   In New York Stock Exchange composite trading yesterday,
Wells Fargo shares closed at $73.50, down $1.375.
</TEXT>
