<HL>
   International Brief -- Marks &amp; Spencer PLC:
   Retailer Reports 14% Rise
   In Pretax Profit for Year
</HL>
<DATE>
05/15/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A21
</SO>
<CO>
   U.MAR
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   Marks &amp; Spencer PLC, a major British clothing and food
retailer, reported a 14% rise in pretax profit for the year
ended March 31, with a strong recovery in Europe offsetting
difficulties in the U.S.
   Marks &amp; Spencer said that pretax profit jumped to #604.2
million ($1.01 billion) in its latest fiscal year from #529
million a year earlier, reaching the upper limit of market
expectations.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Profit after tax less minorities, or net profit
attributable to shareholders, increased 13% to #389 million
from #342.9 million the year before.
   The company reported no extraordinary items for either the
latest period or a year earlier.
   Marks &amp; Spencer's sales rose 9.5% to #5.61 billion from
#5.12 billion.
   The company said it was a "particularly good year" for
ladies' clothing sales in the United Kingdom and Ireland,
with continental Europe also showing a strong recovery in
profit and sales compared with the previous reporting year.
   Difficult trading conditions and severe price-cutting hit
Brooks Brothers, Marks &amp; Spencer's flagship store in the U.S.
But the company's mail-order division "made good increases"
there, the company said.
</TEXT>
