<HL>
   Business Brief -- Apple Bancorp Inc.:
   Holders Requested to Reject
   Proxy Fight by Bidder Stahl
</HL>
<DATE>
05/15/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4
</SO>
<CO>
   APK
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)
</IN>
<LP>
   Apple Bancorp Inc. urged shareholders to reject a proxy
fight organized by Stanley Stahl and affirmed its rejection
of the New York real-estate investor's $38-a-share tender
offer.
   The New York-based parent of Apple Bank for Savings told
shareholders in a letter, "We believe that it is coercive for
Mr. Stahl to condition his offer on having you first vote to
give him control" of Apple before the board "has had a full
opportunity to explore and pursue financially more-attractive
alternatives."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Stahl, who controls 30.6% of Apple and has offered
$121.6 million for the rest, declined to comment on the
letter, which Apple disclosed as part of a Securities and
Exchange Commission filing. The company and Mr. Stahl have
lawsuits pending against each other.
   Apple's directors haven't set a date for the annual
meeting; Mr. Stahl's lawsuit demands, among other things,
that the board set such a date. The company has said that the
board hasn't set the date in order to allow time to explore
alternatives to Mr. Stahl's bid.
   In New York Stock Exchange composite trading yesterday,
Apple shares closed at $44, unchanged.
</TEXT>
