<HL>
   Business Brief -- Patrick Petroleum Co.:
   Company Sells $20 Million
   Of 10.75% Eight-Year Notes
</HL>
<DATE>
05/15/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   PPC WX
</CO>
<IN>
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
</IN>
<LP>
   Patrick Petroleum Co. said it has sold $20 million of
10.75% eight-year subordinated collateralized notes to a
group of institutional investors. Non-callable warrants,
which expire in 1997, to purchase 800,000 shares of Patrick
common stock were also issued to the participants.
   The Jackson, Mich.-based oil and gas exploration company
said it will use proceeds to repay existing credit lines and
provide "additional financial flexibility" to support its
continuing oil and gas acquisition programs.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The notes, which are due in 1998, are secured by Patrick
Petroleum's equity ownership in Penske Corp. and its Penske
Transportation Inc. unit.
   The institutional investors, headed by Westinghouse Credit
Corp. of Pittsburgh, a unit of Westinghouse Electric Corp.,
also include Connecticut Mutual Life Insurance Co. of
Hartford, Conn., and General American Life Insurance Co. of
St. Louis. Boettcher &amp; Co., of Denver, served as the private
placement agent and financial adviser to the company.
   "This is the best way to continue the rapid expansion of
our oil and gas operations while maintaining the benefits of
our Penske securities," said Patrick's president, U.E.
Patrick, in a prepared statement. "We remain committed to our
Penske investments and will continue to receive the benefits
of future dividends and capital appreciation. Also, we will
profit from this fixed-rate component of our capitalization
and our relationship with these substantial financial
institutions."
</TEXT>
