<HL>
   Blinder Wins Reversal
   Of Court Limitation
   On Asset Transfers
</HL>
<DATE>
05/15/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C21
</SO>
<CO>
   ENTI
</CO>
<IN>
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<GV>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
</GV>
<LP>
   ENGLEWOOD, Colo. -- Blinder, Robinson &amp; Co. said that the
Third U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals vacated a preliminary
injunction entered against it almost a year ago that limited
the brokerage's ability to transfer assets outside its
ordinary business.
   Blinder is a unit of Intercontinental Enterprises Inc. and
once was the nation's largest penny-stock broker.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The preliminary injunction was granted in May of last year
by a Philadelphia federal judge, who enjoined Blinder from
transferring assets outside of its ordinary business and
prohibited it from transferring funds overseas without
advance notice or court approval. The judge also ordered
Blinder to return funds transferred to overseas bank accounts
to the U.S.
   However, in late May of 1989, the appeals court agreed to
stay the provisions limiting transfers overseas and the
requirement to return assets from overseas.
   The injunction was issued as part of class-action lawsuits
filed by three groups of former Blinder Robinson customers
who are charging the brokerage with securities fraud,
excessive markups on stocks and racketeering. A trial date
for the lawsuit hasn't been set, a Blinder lawyer said.
   Separately, Intercontinental Enterprises said it had a net
loss of $4.5 million, or six cents a share, for its year
ended Jan. 26, compared with a net loss of $9.6 million, or
13 cents a share, in the previous year. Revenue fell about
50%, to $42.1 million in fiscal 1990 from $84.6 million in
fiscal 1989. The company attributed the revenue decline to a
downturn in the securities industry and said the latest-year
loss includes the cost of closing several Blinder Robinson
offices.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900515-0001
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900515-0001.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Habsburg Feldman
   Auction of Paintings
   Brings Dismal Results
</HL>
<DATE>
05/15/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<CO>
   U.CHR BID
</CO>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- The first auction of impressionist and modern
paintings of the spring art auction season met with dismal
results.
   Habsburg, Feldman Inc., a small, upstart Geneva-based
auction house saw only about 15% of its paintings sell here
last night.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   And while the auction was relativly small in dollar terms,
it set a somber stage for the larger multimillion dollar art
auctions to be held here at Christie's International PLC and
Sotheby's Holdings Inc. later this week.
   Art dealers stress that this first sale wasn't a true test
of the strength of the art market. They contended that unlike
the evening sales later this week, last night's auction was
filled with art works by such weaker painters as Maurice
Utrillo and Maurice de Vlaminck and by some lesser works by
such renowned painters as Claude Monet. Nonetheless, the
percentage of unsold works was almost double that of Habsburg
Feldman's similar sale in November.
   The mood of the room grew increasingly leaden as painting
after painting was passed up by bidders. At one point, to
lighten the mood, auctioneer Archduke Geza von Habsburg
reminded the crowd that bidding was allowed.
   In several cases, in a break with auction tradition,
sellers appeared to have set the minimum price they would
accept at the high end of the presale estimate. That
indicates that the auction house expected much stronger
bidding.
   The top lot of the sale was an oil on canvas of two women
painted by Pierre-Auguste Renoir. It fetched $2.6 million, at
the high end of the presale estimate of $2.3 million to $2.6
million.
   The next major sale will be tonight at Christie's. Up for
bid is Vincent van Gogh's evocative and melancholic
masterpiece "The Portrait of Doctor Gachet." It is estimated
to sell for $40 million or more.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
